summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the 11th century, contains John Chrysostom, In Genesim homiliae , comprising thirty homilies by the Patriarch of Constantinople. Previously owned by the Greek monastery of Pantokratoros (Mount Athos), it was bought by the classical scholar Richard Bentley and bequeathed to Trinity College after his death.

msItem.author: John Chrysostom
msItem.title: Homilies on Genesis 1-30
In Genesim homilae 1-30
msItem.rubric: f. 1r Ὁμιλία αʹ. Τοῦ ἐν ἁγίοις πατρὸς ἡμῶν Ἰωάννου ἀρχιεπισκόπου Κωνσταντινουπόλεως τοῦ Χρυσοστόμου ὁμιλία ῥηθεῖσα εἰς τὴν εἴσοδον τῆς ἁγίας τεσσαρακοστῆς
msItem.incipit: f. 1r Χαίρω καὶ εὐφραίνομαι ὁρῶν σήμερον τὴν τοῦ Θεοῦ Ἐκκλησίαν τῶι πλήθει τῶν οἰκείων τέκνων κοσμουμένην
msItem.explicit: f. 270v ἵνα τῆς παρ’ αὐτοῦ ῥοπῆς ἀξιούμενοι, καὶ τὸν παρόντα βίον εὐαρέστως διανύσωμεν· καὶ ἐν τῶ μέλλοντι φιλανθρωπίας τινὸς ἀξιωθῶμεν· χάριτι καὶ οἰκτιρμοῖς τοῦ Κυρίου ἡμῶν Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ· μεθ’ οὗ τῶ Πατρὶ ἅμα τῶ ἁγίω Πνεύματι, δόξα κράτος τιμὴ, νῦν καὶ ἀεὶ, καὶ εἰς τοὺς αἰῶνας τῶν αἰώνων. Ἀμήν

list.item: Hom. 17: ff. 116r-130v (ends at PG 53, col. 148 line 7)

support.material: ff. 1r-269v: Parchment, medium thickness, medium quality, arranged flesh-to-flesh and hair-to-hair with hair outermost (HFFH).
f. 270, western paper, folded in folio, no watermark visible.

supportDesc.foliation: [i] + 1-269 + 270-[271] + [ii]; Modern foliation in brown ink in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right corner.
supportDesc.collation:
The manuscript consists of 34 quaternions, the last of which lost three folios, and two added folios:
Quires 1-338 ff. 1r-264v
Quire 348-3 ff. 265r-269v
Quire 352 ff. 270r-[271]v
Quire signature, probably original to the production of the manuscript, in Greek numerals on the first recto, inner lower corner, and the last verso, inner lower corner, from f. 8v (αʹ) to f. 265r (λδʹ); κγʹ on f. 177r is missing.
Signature are repeated on lower and upper margins in light brown ink on ff. 8v, 16v, 24v, 25r, 32v, 33r, 40v, 41.

condition.p: In good condition; initial and final leaves rubbed; a few cuts due to ruling (e.g. ff. 18 and 23), some holes (e.g. f. 27) and the margins cut off from ff. 141-142. Outer margins of ff. 268 and 269 have been torn away and replaced with two paper slips with missing text. The last folios in paper are very damaged and fragile.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1r-269v: written space 220 173
32 lines per column. Pricked in the outer margins, pricking survives in several folios. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 44B2s , but the lines for writing are also extended to the edge (index A), e.g. ff. 12, 16, 62.

ff. 270r-270v: written space 220 135
32 lines per column.

handNote.p: The manuscript is written in a Perlschrift script of the 11th century.
The paper addition to the parchment manuscript is written in a mixed minuscule script, imitating the original Perlschrift script.

decoDesc.decoNote: An elaorated colored pyle on f. 1r; other headpieces mark the begining of each homily: homilies 2-9, 19-21, 28-30 in red ink; homilies 10 and 27 in red and green; homilies 11-18, 22, 24 in red, green and yellow; homily 23 in red and yellow; homily 26 in red, yellow and black.
Initials are drawn in the same style as the accompanying headpieces; the more elaborate ones are: ff. 1r (hom. 1), 191v (hom. 24), 204r (hom. 25), 206v (hom. 26), 227v (hom. 27).
Small colored initials in red ink throughout the manuscript.

additions.p: f. 1r: a very shaky hand added τοῦ αγίου ὁνουφρίου τοις ἀχιροπιήτου (sic).
ff. 2r and 3r: ownership notes: ἐξαήμερος μονῆς τοῦ Παντοκράτορος τὴν ἐν τῶ Ἁγίω Ὄρει (sic).
f. 18r: pen-work erased, only letters over the main text remain; f. 227r: a second pen-sketch erased.
f. 144r: a verse with musical notation.
f. 215r: some sketches in black ink.
f. [ii] recto: scribbles and drawings of ships and animals (?), and some headpieces.

binding.p: Wooden boards covered with brown leather, blind-tooled edges. The spine is in light brown skin, with bands tooled in gold and a brown leather label with title: Chrysostomi Homilae in Genesim.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in the 11th century.
history.provenance: The manuscript comes from the Pantokratoros Monastery of Mount Athos (see notes on ff. 2r and 3r). Perhaps it was previously in another monastery or church dedicated to St. Onuphrius but not better identified. It was purchased from Mount Athos by Richard Bentley.
history.acquisition: Bequeathed to Trinity College by Bentley, Richard, 1662-1742 Richard Bentley (1662-1742) , Master of the College.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College, Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, p. 239.
